## Test File Organisation

```
src/
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ modules/
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ users/
        ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ users.service.ts
        ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ users.service.unit.test.ts    # Unit tests beside the source
        ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ users.controller.int.test.ts  # Integration tests beside the source

tests/
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ e2e/
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ auth.e2e.ts                       # E2E tests in a top-level folder
```

- Use suffixes to distinguish test types: `.unit.test.ts`, `.int.test.ts`, `.e2e.ts`
- Keep test files **next to the code they test** for unit/integration; use a top-level `tests/e2e/` for E2E

---

## Coverage

- Aim for **80%+ line coverage** as a floor ‚Äî not a goal
- Coverage does not equal quality ‚Äî 100% coverage with bad assertions is worse than 70% with good ones
- Use **branch coverage** as the meaningful metric, not just line coverage
- Block merges below the coverage threshold in CI, but do not chase coverage for its own sake
- Identify **untested critical paths** (auth, payments, data mutations) and prioritise those specifically

---

## CI Integration

- Run **unit tests** on every push (fast, < 2 min)
- Run **integration tests** on every PR (< 10 min)
- Run **E2E tests** on merge to `main` or on a schedule (< 20 min)
- Fail the pipeline on **any test failure** ‚Äî a broken test is as bad as broken code
- Report coverage deltas on PRs ‚Äî flag when a PR reduces coverage significantly
- Parallelise test suites for large projects; use test sharding (`--shard`) in Vitest/Jest/pytest

---

## Test Data

- Use **factories** (`factory_boy`, `fishery`, `@faker-js/faker`) over hard-coded fixtures
- Never use production data in tests ‚Äî even anonymised
- Seed only what the test needs (minimal fixtures)
- Use **deterministic seeds** for random data in tests so failures are reproducible
